@coach and @wearebraindead carnival-like collab arrives just as the fashion world threatens to move on from trinket maximalism, doubling down instead on charms, plush mascots, pins, patches, and all things ornamented. Debuting via a surprise flash runway in NYCвҖҷs Meatpacking District, the collection spans retro womenswear, vintage sportswear-inspired menswear, leather goods, and accessories overloaded with fictional cartoon mascots, glossy plastic charms, and souvenir-style graphics. Think O-ring suede jackets jangling with keychains, bias-cut gingham skirts, rugby polos, mesh jerseys, and bags practically buried beneath adornments.вҒ 
вҒ 
For Brain Dead co-founder Kyle Ng and Coach Creative Director Stuart Vevers, the project became less about individual products and more about building a fully immersive universe inspired by Tokyo street style, вҖҳ90s revivals of вҖҳ70s fashion, theme park souvenirs, and Y2K-era collectible culture. The result feels intentionally chaotic in the spirit of FRUiTS Magazine, where personalization, humor, and nostalgia collide. Standouts like the plush pink bear bag, charm-covered Tabby, and cartoon lunchbox bags prove the collabвҖҷs biggest success lies in its accessories, making a convincing argument that fashionвҖҷs obsession with trinkets is far from over.

